                        <item>
                           <note xml:lang="en"><p>
<lb/>                                        Avraham E. Harkavy (1835–1919) was one of the most important</p><p>                              Russian Orientalist of the 19th century. He received his doctoral degree in</p><p>                              1872. During the same year, he was attached to the Ministry of National</p><p>                              Education. On June 1, 1872, he was commissioned to the Imperial Public</p><p>                              Library in St. Petersburg to sort and study the manuscripts of the First</p><p>                              Firkovitch Collection and the Samaritan Collections. The following years,</p><p>                              Harkavy collaborated with Hermann Strack of Leipzig University in the New</p><p>                              (Mangup) Synagogue in Chufut-Qal’eh on examining and sorting the manuscripts</p><p>                              of the Second Firkovitch Collection which was subsequently acquired by the</p><p>                              Imperial Public Library in 1876. On January 9, 1876, he was appointed a</p><p>                              librarian there by order of Emperor Alexander II, and made head of the</p><p>                              Department of Hebrew Books. He was the first curator of the Firkovitch</p><p>                              collections. His unpublished cataloging of these collections consists of</p><p>                              slips of paper ("Harkavy cards"), placed together with each manuscript, that</p><p>                              record his identification of and/or a brief description of that manuscript.</p><p>                              These slips were the foundation for his handwritten four-volume inventory of</p><p>                              the Yevr.-Arab. section of the Second Firkovitch Collection. (Daria</p><p>                              Vasyutinsky Shapira, Early Stages of Research of the Firkowicz Collections</p><p>                              Manuscripts: The Emergence of Russian Jewish Studies. PhD thesis,</p><p>                              Beer-Sheva: Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, 2018, pp. 121–182).</p><p>
<lb/>                                    </p></note>
                           <persName>Avraham Harkavy</persName>
                           <quote xml:lang="ru"><p>
<lb/>                                        </p><p>                              p. 4<lb/>  </p><p>                              N. 19 (372)<lb/>  </p><p>                              Изъ коммент. Jeфета на Второзаконіе (на 1ой стр. приписка)<lb/>  </p><p>                              N. 20 (372)<lb/>  </p><p>                              Изъ коммент. Второзаконіе Jeфета (въ концѣ отд. שופטים трехстишіе, имѣющ. въ акростихѣ Хасанъ - араб. эквивалентъ евр. Jeфета<lb/>  </p><p>                              I<lb/>  </p><p>                              p. 5<lb/>  </p><p>                              N. 19 (372)<lb/>  </p><p>                              Изъ коммент. Jeфета на Второзаконіе<lb/>  </p><p>                              II<lb/>  </p><p>                              133 134 л.<lb/>  </p><p>                              22.10.93 [подпись]<lb/>  </p><p>                              corresponds to p. 2<lb/>  </p><p>                              LR<lb/> </p><p>
